1
00:00:14,670 --> 00:00:17,161
(Birds twittering)

2
00:01:10,810 --> 00:01:12,886
(Coughing)

3
00:01:18,234 --> 00:01:21,768
Fire! Fire in the hole.

4
00:01:21,821 --> 00:01:24,146
(Distant voice) Fire in the hole!

5
00:01:26,659 --> 00:01:28,735
(Explosion)

6
00:01:30,162 --> 00:01:33,448
Let's get it, boys.
Always loads easy on payday.

7
00:01:35,793 --> 00:01:37,869
(Steam train puffing)

8
00:02:11,162 --> 00:02:13,238
(Klaxon)

9
00:02:16,667 --> 00:02:21,246
Hi, Daddy. Look at your knee.
Why don't you wear your knee pad?

10
00:02:21,964 --> 00:02:24,881
Loretty, that old shaft's so low,

11
00:02:24,925 --> 00:02:27,843
you wear your knee pads,
you skin your back.

12
00:02:27,887 --> 00:02:30,722
If you don't wear 'em,
you skin your knees.

13
00:02:30,764 --> 00:02:34,015
I'll wear 'em tomorrow
and give my back a turn.

14
00:02:35,352 --> 00:02:38,437
Boys, there ain't no place
this thing can't take me.

15
00:02:38,480 --> 00:02:42,099
There ain't a creek she can't ford
or a hill she can't climb.

16
00:02:42,151 --> 00:02:46,279
I know a thing she can't climb.
That heap of red dog.

17
00:02:46,322 --> 00:02:49,406
I can climb that
in a by-God New York minute.

18
00:02:49,450 --> 00:02:51,027
- Shit!
- Hey!

19
00:02:51,076 --> 00:02:54,695
You boys watch your language
in front of these kids.

20
00:02:57,208 --> 00:03:01,953
All right, does anybody wanna bet me
I can't climb that mess there?

21
00:03:02,004 --> 00:03:04,875
- (Man) That pile up there?
- Hell yes! I can...

22
00:03:04,924 --> 00:03:07,593
Oh, I'm sorry, little girl. Excuse me.

23
00:03:07,635 --> 00:03:09,841
(2nd man) It can't be done.

24
00:03:09,887 --> 00:03:13,587
I got me $25 that says I can do it.
Does anybody wanna bet me?

25
00:03:14,683 --> 00:03:18,052
- (Murmuring)
- (Soldier) I'll take all of it.

26
00:03:18,103 --> 00:03:20,725
Come on, kids. Let's get to the store.

27
00:03:20,773 --> 00:03:23,809
(Both) Give the company
their money back.

28
00:03:25,402 --> 00:03:27,478
Loretta, come on, honey.

29
00:03:27,529 --> 00:03:30,733
(Men shouting out bets)

30
00:03:32,576 --> 00:03:34,948
- Hi, Ted.
- Hey, Colin.

31
00:03:36,038 --> 00:03:40,617
Who's that soldier boy
strutting around like a bantam rooster?

32
00:03:40,668 --> 00:03:43,455
It's old man Red Lynn's boy. Doolittle.

33
00:03:43,504 --> 00:03:47,632
Come back from the army
acting like a wild heathen.

34
00:03:47,675 --> 00:03:51,838
He'll calm down a soon as they slap
a coal shovel in his hand.

35
00:03:52,930 --> 00:03:56,630
- That Sears Roebuck order come in yet?
- I'll get it for you.

36
00:03:56,684 --> 00:03:59,554
- (Engine revs)
- (Doolittle) All right.

37
00:03:59,603 --> 00:04:02,889
Loretty, get you and Herman
a jar of Viennas.

38
00:04:15,828 --> 00:04:18,283
(Crowd jeering)

39
00:04:18,330 --> 00:04:21,000
(Miner) Get your mule, son.

40
00:04:22,835 --> 00:04:27,129
Hey, Cousin Ted, come on in here
and get in on this bet, a sure thing.

41
00:04:27,172 --> 00:04:30,707
Doolittle will never get up there
without rolling over.

42
00:04:47,276 --> 00:04:49,150
(Engine straining)

43
00:04:54,575 --> 00:04:56,152
(Gears grinding)

44
00:05:07,588 --> 00:05:10,589
(Crowd booing)

45
00:05:10,632 --> 00:05:14,844
Lord, that son of a gun Doolittle
don't know what quit means.

46
00:05:14,887 --> 00:05:19,845
He sure went to a lot of trouble
to get on top of a pile of junk.

47
00:05:19,892 --> 00:05:21,968
(Ted) Come on, Herman.

48
00:05:23,604 --> 00:05:25,929
(Young boy) Mommy, Daddy's home!

49
00:05:25,981 --> 00:05:28,104
(2nd boy) What's in that box?

50
00:05:28,150 --> 00:05:32,148
(Ted) Something special.
Don't open it till we get inside.

51
00:05:33,906 --> 00:05:36,029
(Children shouting excitedly)

52
00:05:39,203 --> 00:05:43,070
(Woman) Y'all get washed up
before you come in.

53
00:05:43,123 --> 00:05:46,373
Y'all hear your Momma?
Everybody go wash now.

54
00:05:52,800 --> 00:05:55,088
(Gun being cocked)

55
00:05:55,135 --> 00:05:57,424
Lee Dollarhide.

56
00:05:58,597 --> 00:06:02,298
Come on in here, Doo.
I was just about to blast you one.

57
00:06:08,148 --> 00:06:11,731
Old boy down at the store
said you wanted to see me.

58
00:06:11,777 --> 00:06:13,935
Here, take you a sip.

59
00:06:16,407 --> 00:06:18,280
OK, fellas.

60
00:06:19,910 --> 00:06:23,445
- Donald Ray.
- Thanks, Daddy.

61
00:06:24,540 --> 00:06:26,616
Jack. Hand that to brother Jack.

62
00:06:26,667 --> 00:06:29,454
- Thank you.
- (Mother) Take the baby, Jack.

63
00:06:29,503 --> 00:06:31,579
(Ted) How do they feel, gang?

64
00:06:31,630 --> 00:06:33,872
Daddy, Peggy got two right feet.

65
00:06:33,924 --> 00:06:36,130
- (Ted) What?
- Two right shoes.

66
00:06:36,176 --> 00:06:39,711
(Ted) I'll be darned. Don't worry.
We'll get 'em changed.

67
00:06:39,763 --> 00:06:42,433
- (Mother) How they feel?
- Loretta.

68
00:06:42,933 --> 00:06:47,928
(Jack) Get your hands off.
Leave him alone, Donald Ray.

69
00:06:47,980 --> 00:06:51,396
- (Baby crying)
- Daddy.

70
00:06:51,442 --> 00:06:55,570
Hey, how come she gets
something extra?

71
00:06:55,612 --> 00:06:59,231
Jack, Loretta's getting to be a woman.
Going on 14.

72
00:06:59,283 --> 00:07:01,738
Women s'posed to have pretty things.

73
00:07:01,785 --> 00:07:05,830
She ain't no woman.
She ain't nothing but a dadburned kid.

74
00:07:05,873 --> 00:07:07,949
What are you, Herman?

75
00:07:09,042 --> 00:07:12,162
(Kids laughing, door slams)

76
00:07:22,139 --> 00:07:25,009
Remember when
you used to work for me,

77
00:07:25,058 --> 00:07:29,519
- sell my goods at the mines?
- You paid a nickel for every jug I sold.

78
00:07:29,563 --> 00:07:33,892
- How'd you like to work for me again?
- Not for no nickel a jug!

79
00:07:36,069 --> 00:07:38,477
I'm talking about real money, Doo.

80
00:07:38,530 --> 00:07:42,398
Business is good. I'm selling
more whiskey than I can make.

81
00:07:42,451 --> 00:07:46,318
I heard you'd been stealing some
from the boys in Greasy Creek.

82
00:07:46,371 --> 00:07:48,447
Just when I run shy of my own.

83
00:07:51,418 --> 00:07:55,202
I'm fixing to make me another run
on Greasy Creek.

84
00:07:55,255 --> 00:07:57,580
You got that Jeep.

85
00:07:57,633 --> 00:08:00,717
You know how to use a gun
and you can use you a job.

86
00:08:01,720 --> 00:08:03,760
I'll go fifty-fifty with you.

87
00:08:07,100 --> 00:08:11,928
Doo, if you're born in the mountains,
you got three choices -

88
00:08:11,980 --> 00:08:15,266
coal mine, moonshine

89
00:08:15,317 --> 00:08:17,725
or moving on down the line.

90
00:08:30,707 --> 00:08:33,661
- (Song turns to static)
- Get your feet off!

91
00:08:33,710 --> 00:08:37,459
Turn the radio off.
We can't afford no new batteries.

92
00:08:40,717 --> 00:08:44,217
You got one of
your bad headaches again, Daddy?

93
00:08:44,263 --> 00:08:46,469
Do you want me to mix
up some medicine?

94
00:08:46,515 --> 00:08:48,840
It don't do no good. It'll pass.

95
00:08:49,935 --> 00:08:53,470
- What you see in them grounds?
- (Ted) Loretty, take the baby.

96
00:08:53,522 --> 00:08:57,520
I see a woman crying.
Looks to me like a man crying, too.

97
00:08:57,568 --> 00:08:59,644
- Who are they?
- (Mouthing)

98
00:09:01,154 --> 00:09:03,776
Loretty.

99
00:09:03,824 --> 00:09:08,699
- What are they crying about, Mommy?
- Take the baby out and rock her.

100
00:09:10,122 --> 00:09:12,031
Bad times is a-coming.

101
00:09:12,082 --> 00:09:15,581
Well, we don't need no fortune-teller
to know that.

102
00:09:17,181 --> 00:09:19,900
♪ In the pines, in the pines ♪

103
00:09:19,923 --> 00:09:23,126
♪ Where the sun never shines ♪

104
00:09:23,176 --> 00:09:28,218
♪ And I shiver when the cold wind blows ♪

105
00:09:29,308 --> 00:09:32,641
♪ The longest train ♪

106
00:09:32,686 --> 00:09:35,603
♪ I ever saw... ♪

107
00:09:35,647 --> 00:09:41,317
- (Gun cocks)
- ♪ Was on that Georgia Line ♪

108
00:09:41,361 --> 00:09:44,481
♪ The purtiest boy ♪

109
00:09:44,531 --> 00:09:47,485
♪ I ever saw ♪

110
00:09:47,534 --> 00:09:52,694
♪ Was on that caboose behind ♪

111
00:09:53,790 --> 00:09:55,664
♪ In the pines... ♪♪

112
00:09:55,709 --> 00:09:58,626
(Gunshot echoes across valley)

113
00:10:22,027 --> 00:10:26,072
Good thing you wasn't working for him.
You'd be by his side.

114
00:10:26,114 --> 00:10:27,573
I know that, Daddy.

115
00:10:27,616 --> 00:10:32,077
Course if you had, at least you'd have
been working somewhere.

116
00:10:59,356 --> 00:11:02,606
- (Fast bluegrass)
- (Clapping and whooping)

117
00:11:26,967 --> 00:11:28,212
(Music stops)

118
00:11:28,260 --> 00:11:31,214
(Woman) You're out.
That's all right, you did fine.

119
00:11:31,263 --> 00:11:32,887
(Music restarts)

120
00:11:32,931 --> 00:11:35,802
Get up and dance!

121
00:11:41,148 --> 00:11:45,228
Preacher Banks was supposed
to be here to auction off these pies.

122
00:11:45,277 --> 00:11:49,903
- He's sick and I...
- I can't take no time to auction no pies.

123
00:11:49,948 --> 00:11:55,287
If these girls want to eat pies with a boy,
they'll do it if there's an auction or not.

124
00:11:56,288 --> 00:11:58,861
I'll auction off them pies for you.

125
00:11:58,915 --> 00:12:00,825
- You will?
- I sure will.

126
00:12:00,876 --> 00:12:04,708
Six bits? Got six bits there.
Who's gonna bid a dollar?

127
00:12:04,755 --> 00:12:06,996
- (Boy) I will!
- We got a dollar here.

128
00:12:07,048 --> 00:12:10,749
It's a dollar one time.
Boys, that's a dollar twice.

129
00:12:10,802 --> 00:12:13,340
That's sold right there for a dollar.

130
00:12:14,639 --> 00:12:17,806
- Give me that dollar right there.
- Thank you.

131
00:12:24,149 --> 00:12:28,526
All right, we got one pie left.
It's a chocolate pie belonging to...

132
00:12:28,570 --> 00:12:30,479
Loretta Webb.

133
00:12:31,573 --> 00:12:34,146
Who's gonna bid first?

134
00:12:34,201 --> 00:12:37,285
- I bid two bits.
- Buddy, that's an insult!

135
00:12:37,329 --> 00:12:41,623
Who's gonna start it off for a dollar?
Who'll give me a dollar, now?

136
00:12:44,419 --> 00:12:47,254
I guess I get it, then.

137
00:12:47,297 --> 00:12:51,710
- Heck, I'll bid a dollar, buddy.
- You ain't supposed to bid.

138
00:12:51,760 --> 00:12:54,547
- A dollar once, a dollar twice...
- A dollar and a dime.

139
00:12:54,596 --> 00:12:58,463
- Three dollars.
- That ain't fair, he's cheating!

140
00:12:58,517 --> 00:13:01,553
- Three dollars once, twice...
- Three and a dime.

141
00:13:01,603 --> 00:13:05,553
- Three seventy-five.
- Three seventy... seven.

142
00:13:05,607 --> 00:13:08,312
(Laughter)

143
00:13:08,360 --> 00:13:11,480
- Five dollars.
- (Crowd gasps)

144
00:13:13,156 --> 00:13:17,403
(Quickly) Once, twice,
sold to Mr. Doolittle for five dollars.

145
00:13:21,206 --> 00:13:24,741
Play in the house
and play in the sea

146
00:13:24,793 --> 00:13:27,200
And when that pretty girl turns to me

147
00:13:28,588 --> 00:13:31,210
Swing her high and swing her low

148
00:13:32,384 --> 00:13:34,460
Swing your partner, do-si-do

149
00:13:36,054 --> 00:13:39,637
Takes that lamb
and takes that squirrel

150
00:13:39,683 --> 00:13:42,553
Takes that pretty girl
round the world...

151
00:13:52,404 --> 00:13:56,698
- Make a lot of chocolate pies?
- Not too many, except this one.

152
00:14:01,580 --> 00:14:03,703
(Coughs)

153
00:14:04,791 --> 00:14:07,329
How much salt did that recipe call for?

154
00:14:07,377 --> 00:14:11,291
You don't put no salt in chocolate pie.
Just sugar and...

155
00:14:13,091 --> 00:14:15,131
You must have got 'em mixed up.

156
00:14:16,219 --> 00:14:19,386
Makes sense, though.
Salt and sugar both white.

157
00:14:25,228 --> 00:14:28,182
(Square dance caller continues)

158
00:14:31,943 --> 00:14:35,727
There ain't no sense in walking
when you can ride. Come on!

159
00:14:35,780 --> 00:14:39,992
- I ain't gettin' in that.
- You ain't never rode in a car before?

160
00:14:40,035 --> 00:14:43,653
That ain't no car.
It looks like something from Mars.

161
00:14:43,705 --> 00:14:48,201
Mars? Gal, what the hell do you know
about Mars anyway?

162
00:14:48,251 --> 00:14:52,878
I bet you ain't never been past
the mouth of this hollow.

163
00:14:52,923 --> 00:14:57,798
- Come on, get in this thing.
- I said I ain't gettin' in it and I ain't!

164
00:14:57,844 --> 00:15:00,845
If you like me so much,
you can walk me home.

165
00:15:01,932 --> 00:15:06,225
Oh, Lord, them pies ain't the only thing
salty about you.

166
00:15:06,269 --> 00:15:08,392
Wait! We'll walk it, then.

167
00:15:08,438 --> 00:15:10,514
(Machinery hums)

168
00:15:12,692 --> 00:15:17,650
The first time I ever seen you I said
me and that gal's gonna get together.

169
00:15:17,697 --> 00:15:21,446
I saw you, too. In that little soldier suit.

170
00:15:21,493 --> 00:15:24,696
I thought you looked just like
a toy soldier.

171
00:15:24,746 --> 00:15:28,197
I went ashore on D-day plus four and
I stayed until the damn thing was over.

172
00:15:29,793 --> 00:15:32,081
I wasn't no little old toy soldier.

173
00:15:34,381 --> 00:15:36,872
You know what D-day is, don't you?

174
00:15:39,636 --> 00:15:41,759
- What?
- Never mind.

175
00:15:45,850 --> 00:15:48,935
Tell you one thing
that army showed me -

176
00:15:48,979 --> 00:15:51,683
there's a whole big world out yonder.

177
00:15:54,442 --> 00:15:59,235
Showed me I ain't about to spend my life
buried in no coal mine, neither.

178
00:15:59,280 --> 00:16:04,655
There ain't no damn future in it and
that's what I'm interested in - the future.

179
00:16:04,703 --> 00:16:06,944
You got any plans for the future?

180
00:16:08,373 --> 00:16:11,706
- Huh?
- Not that I know of.

181
00:16:12,919 --> 00:16:15,375
- You sure cuss a lot.
- Yeah, I do.

182
00:16:15,422 --> 00:16:17,794
Cuss, drink, chase wild women.

183
00:16:17,841 --> 00:16:19,798
What? What are you doing?

184
00:16:19,843 --> 00:16:24,255
I'm gonna kiss you good night.
Ain't you ever been kissed before?

185
00:16:40,530 --> 00:16:42,273
Hey, Loretta?

186
00:16:42,323 --> 00:16:45,277
I'm gonna bring my Jeep here
and take you for a ride.

187
00:16:45,326 --> 00:16:47,449
You ain't gonna get that up here.

188
00:16:47,495 --> 00:16:50,165
There ain't nothing I can't do, once I...

189
00:16:50,206 --> 00:16:53,041
(Pigs squealing, dog barking)

190
00:16:55,754 --> 00:16:59,538
(Mother) Loretty, honey,
take Peggy Sue in and feed her.

191
00:17:04,054 --> 00:17:06,295
(Car approaching)

192
00:17:07,390 --> 00:17:10,973
Stranger coming! Stranger coming!

193
00:17:12,103 --> 00:17:13,728
Stranger coming!

194
00:17:16,733 --> 00:17:18,607
Stranger coming!

195
00:17:20,528 --> 00:17:21,987
(Mother) What is it?

196
00:17:26,493 --> 00:17:31,404
I told you I'd get this thing up here.
You gotta take a ride with me now.

197
00:17:46,179 --> 00:17:48,053
(Toots horn)

198
00:18:10,495 --> 00:18:12,820
- Hey, Bill.
- Hey, Doo.

199
00:18:14,415 --> 00:18:17,203
(Truck and Jeep blast horns in turn)

200
00:18:28,513 --> 00:18:30,387
(Tyres squealing)

201
00:18:50,326 --> 00:18:53,411
I can't breathe. I feel like I'm gonna faint.

202
00:18:53,454 --> 00:18:56,455
- That's because you're in love.
- It is?

203
00:18:56,499 --> 00:18:58,373
Yep.

204
00:19:04,257 --> 00:19:06,131
(Dog barking outside)

205
00:19:09,512 --> 00:19:12,466
(Jeep screeches to halt outside)

206
00:19:15,059 --> 00:19:17,550
(Jeep engine revs)

207
00:19:20,732 --> 00:19:22,641
Where have you been?

208
00:19:24,444 --> 00:19:27,279
- Doolittle took me riding.
- What?

209
00:19:27,322 --> 00:19:30,691
- Doolittle took me riding.
- Took you riding?

210
00:19:30,742 --> 00:19:34,360
You just run off.
Didn't ask nobody or nothing.

211
00:19:34,412 --> 00:19:37,413
Run off and worry everybody to death.

212
00:19:48,676 --> 00:19:50,752
Y'all get to bed. Go on.

213
00:20:08,905 --> 00:20:12,950
He'd rather cut off his arm
than have to whip you like that.

214
00:20:13,952 --> 00:20:16,952
What you want
running off with that wild boy?

215
00:20:16,996 --> 00:20:19,072
I love him, Mommy.

216
00:20:20,166 --> 00:20:22,574
You do no such a thing.

217
00:20:22,627 --> 00:20:27,621
Stay away from Doolittle or I'll give you
worse than what your Daddy did.

218
00:20:28,716 --> 00:20:30,839
Get some salve for your legs.

219
00:21:11,092 --> 00:21:15,386
Loretty, you know
I don't like to boss you

220
00:21:15,430 --> 00:21:17,303
but I got to now, honey.

221
00:21:17,348 --> 00:21:19,970
- Daddy...
- Just let me talk.

222
00:21:20,018 --> 00:21:23,268
Doolittle's been up the house
every day this week.

223
00:21:23,313 --> 00:21:25,804
- I don't want him hanging around.
- Why?

224
00:21:25,857 --> 00:21:29,689
Cos you ain't got no business
hanging around with him.

225
00:21:29,736 --> 00:21:32,939
You're just a little girl,
he's a grown-up man,

226
00:21:32,989 --> 00:21:35,658
wild as the devil.

227
00:21:35,700 --> 00:21:37,989
I love him, Daddy.

228
00:21:38,036 --> 00:21:40,953
And he's a-wanting me to marry him.

229
00:21:42,540 --> 00:21:45,078
You ain't even 14 yet.

230
00:21:46,919 --> 00:21:51,498
- Y'all ain't knowed each other a month.
- I know.

231
00:21:51,549 --> 00:21:53,625
But I love him.

232
00:21:53,676 --> 00:21:57,010
Lord, Lord, don't do it, Loretty.

233
00:21:58,097 --> 00:22:01,513
Don't throw all them young years away.

234
00:22:01,559 --> 00:22:04,928
You're my pride, girl. My shining pride.

235
00:22:08,441 --> 00:22:10,517
I just can't help it.

236
00:22:11,611 --> 00:22:14,184
I can't.

237
00:22:19,035 --> 00:22:21,952
(Boys chatting, indistinct)

238
00:22:27,168 --> 00:22:31,000
(Man on radio)
<i>Presenting the Grand Ole Opry.</i>

239
00:22:31,047 --> 00:22:34,831
- <i>Let her go, boys.</i>
- (Bluegrass)

240
00:22:34,884 --> 00:22:37,968
Get up, Mommy. Do your squaw dance.

241
00:22:38,012 --> 00:22:41,428
See if we can't get a smile
out of old sourpuss here.

242
00:22:41,474 --> 00:22:45,139
- Yeah, come on, Momma.
- Come on, Clary.

243
00:22:55,488 --> 00:22:59,533
(Ted singing with radio)
♪ Blue moon of Kentucky keep on shinin' ♪

244
00:22:59,575 --> 00:23:03,703
♪ Shine on the one that's gone
and left me blue ♪

245
00:23:03,746 --> 00:23:07,874
♪ Blue moon of Kentucky keep on shinin' ♪

246
00:23:07,917 --> 00:23:11,368
♪ Shine on the one that's gone
and left me blue... ♪

247
00:23:12,213 --> 00:23:16,127
(Radio) <i>♪ It was on a moonlit night,
the stars shining bright ♪</i>

248
00:23:16,175 --> 00:23:20,636
<i>♪ They whispered from high,
your love said goodbye ♪</i>

249
00:23:20,680 --> 00:23:24,724
<i>♪ Blue moon of Kentucky keep on shinin' ♪</i>

250
00:23:24,767 --> 00:23:27,258
<i>♪ Shine on the one that's gone... ♪♪</i>

251
00:23:27,311 --> 00:23:30,977
(Doolittle) I knocked
but I reckon y'all couldn't hear me.

252
00:23:43,119 --> 00:23:46,452
- Guess I broke up the party.
- It don't matter.

253
00:23:46,497 --> 00:23:48,953
Come on and sit down.

254
00:23:49,000 --> 00:23:51,039
Go on, Donald Ray.

255
00:23:52,587 --> 00:23:55,588
Y'all get out or I'm gonna
knock the tar out of you.

256
00:23:55,631 --> 00:23:58,798
- Why? We're playing chequers.
- Jack, go on.

257
00:23:58,843 --> 00:24:01,879
- Say please.
- Herman?

258
00:24:01,929 --> 00:24:05,298
Junior, come on, take 'em out. Please?

259
00:24:06,184 --> 00:24:08,805
- Come on, let's go.
- Purty please.

260
00:24:11,689 --> 00:24:13,931
Look here at this.

261
00:24:15,026 --> 00:24:18,110
My gosh, Doo.

262
00:24:18,154 --> 00:24:22,448
- Where'd you get all that?
- Paychecks. I've been saving.

263
00:24:22,492 --> 00:24:25,861
You know what tomorrow is?
It's our anniversary.

264
00:24:25,912 --> 00:24:28,663
Get a little closer.

265
00:24:28,706 --> 00:24:30,782
Herman, I'm gonna kill you!

266
00:24:34,837 --> 00:24:38,965
- What were you saying, Doo?
- Tomorrow is our anniversary.

267
00:24:39,008 --> 00:24:42,294
I figured it'd be a good day
for us to get married,

268
00:24:42,345 --> 00:24:45,014
especially since I got all that money.

269
00:24:47,225 --> 00:24:49,431
(Sighs)

270
00:24:51,020 --> 00:24:53,096
Go ask Daddy.

271
00:25:06,452 --> 00:25:11,529
Mr. Webb, me and Loretta is fixing
to get married if it's all right with you.

272
00:25:11,582 --> 00:25:13,871
Tomorrow.

273
00:25:22,260 --> 00:25:24,003
Go ask Clary.

274
00:25:38,317 --> 00:25:40,310
Mrs. Webb, erm, me...

275
00:25:41,988 --> 00:25:45,487
me and Loretty was thinking about
getting married...

276
00:25:45,533 --> 00:25:47,324
tomorrow.

277
00:25:50,496 --> 00:25:52,572
Go ask Ted.

278
00:26:05,428 --> 00:26:07,504
(Herman) Where's lover boy?

279
00:26:09,682 --> 00:26:11,758
Doolittle, what are you doing?

280
00:26:11,809 --> 00:26:15,474
Ted said to ask Clary
and Clary said to ask Ted and...

281
00:26:15,521 --> 00:26:18,392
- I don't know.
- Come on and sit down.

282
00:26:20,484 --> 00:26:23,984
Wait'll they go to bed,
then you can catch them together

283
00:26:24,030 --> 00:26:26,402
else they'll run you about all night.

284
00:26:28,117 --> 00:26:29,991
Mr. and Mrs. Webb?

285
00:26:34,498 --> 00:26:37,618
I know everything's happened real fast.

286
00:26:37,668 --> 00:26:41,203
I know she's young,
I know how much y'all love her

287
00:26:41,255 --> 00:26:44,339
but the deal is...

288
00:26:44,383 --> 00:26:46,755
I love her too.

289
00:26:46,802 --> 00:26:48,878
Just as much as you do.

290
00:26:50,514 --> 00:26:54,215
I growed up real fast,
I seen a lot of the world.

291
00:26:54,268 --> 00:26:59,808
First time I seen that girl I said
that's all I'm ever gonna want out of life.

292
00:26:59,857 --> 00:27:01,600
And I promise you

293
00:27:02,693 --> 00:27:06,821
I'm gonna break my back
working to make her happy.

294
00:27:07,907 --> 00:27:11,323
I reckon y'all set on it
no matter what we say.

295
00:27:12,578 --> 00:27:16,790
I don't wanna go against y'all
but yes'm, we're set on it.

296
00:27:20,336 --> 00:27:23,539
Two things I want you
to promise me, boy.

297
00:27:23,589 --> 00:27:25,665
Don't you never hit her

298
00:27:26,801 --> 00:27:30,252
and don't take her off
far away from home.

299
00:27:30,304 --> 00:27:32,048
Yes, sir.

300
00:27:32,098 --> 00:27:34,174
I promise you that.

301
00:28:02,878 --> 00:28:04,954
Wilt thou love her, comfort her,

302
00:28:05,005 --> 00:28:07,710
honour and keep her
in sickness and in health

303
00:28:07,758 --> 00:28:11,803
and keep thee only unto her
so long as you both shall live?

304
00:28:11,846 --> 00:28:13,388
I will.

305
00:28:13,431 --> 00:28:16,634
Loretta, wilt thou have this man
to be thy wedded husband,

306
00:28:16,684 --> 00:28:19,471
to live together
in the holy estate of matrimony?

307
00:28:19,520 --> 00:28:21,513
Wilt thy love him, comfort him,

308
00:28:21,564 --> 00:28:24,600
honour and keep him
in sickness and in health

309
00:28:24,650 --> 00:28:28,185
and keep thee only unto him
so long as you both shall live?

310
00:28:28,237 --> 00:28:30,194
Mm-hm, yeah, I will.

311
00:28:30,239 --> 00:28:33,573
Who giveth this woman
to be married to this man?

312
00:28:35,870 --> 00:28:38,158
I do.

313
00:28:38,205 --> 00:28:40,281
Please join right hands.

314
00:28:43,461 --> 00:28:47,921
The wedding ring is a visible sign
of an inward and spiritual grace

315
00:28:47,965 --> 00:28:52,793
signifying the uniting of
this man and woman in holy matrimony.

316
00:28:52,845 --> 00:28:55,217
Do you two have rings?

317
00:28:55,264 --> 00:28:57,257
I ain't got no ring, Judge.

318
00:29:14,158 --> 00:29:17,159
She'll warm up here in just a minute.

319
00:29:17,203 --> 00:29:19,528
I got a present for you from Momma.

320
00:29:21,373 --> 00:29:23,947
(Doo unzips trousers and urinates)

321
00:29:30,508 --> 00:29:32,381
(Toilet flushes)

322
00:29:49,944 --> 00:29:52,861
Go on and get ready for bed,
baby, come on.

323
00:30:17,721 --> 00:30:19,963
(Lorries passing outside)

324
00:30:27,606 --> 00:30:30,809
You don't wear a nightgown
over your clothes.

325
00:30:30,860 --> 00:30:33,267
I'm freezing, Doo.

326
00:30:33,320 --> 00:30:38,481
(Laughs) Get on in there and take off
everything but your nightgown.

327
00:30:38,534 --> 00:30:40,776
Go on, Loretty.

328
00:30:40,828 --> 00:30:42,655
Go on!

329
00:30:42,705 --> 00:30:44,781
Go. Go on, now.

330
00:31:31,253 --> 00:31:33,542
(Loretta) Don't do that. Don't!

331
00:31:33,589 --> 00:31:37,669
- Doo, no!
- It's just a little rough the first time.

332
00:31:37,718 --> 00:31:41,467
- Don't worry. Come on, baby.
- (Loretta crying out)

333
00:31:41,513 --> 00:31:44,265
Hush, Loretty.

334
00:31:44,308 --> 00:31:47,807
(Gasping and sobbing) No! No.

335
00:32:18,842 --> 00:32:20,586
This stuff's cold.

336
00:32:21,679 --> 00:32:24,679
It froze between here and the restaurant.

337
00:32:24,723 --> 00:32:26,965
You want a hot breakfast, go with me.

338
00:32:27,017 --> 00:32:32,806
I ain't having all them people looking
at me knowing what we've been doing.

339
00:32:32,856 --> 00:32:37,933
Do you think this is something the rest
of the world ain't caught on to yet?

340
00:32:40,280 --> 00:32:44,444
- It's a little rough the first time.
- Didn't seem too rough on you.

341
00:32:44,493 --> 00:32:46,818
Get used to it cos a marriage...

342
00:32:46,870 --> 00:32:51,331
I ain't gonna get used to you
getting on me and sweating like a pig!

343
00:32:55,212 --> 00:32:59,210
You told Daddy you wouldn't hit me
and look at you already.

344
00:32:59,258 --> 00:33:01,963
I'm sorry, Loretta, but you drove me to it!

345
00:33:10,310 --> 00:33:12,848
(Train horn)

346
00:33:23,240 --> 00:33:25,316
(Dog barking)

347
00:33:33,792 --> 00:33:35,785
Hi, hon.

348
00:33:42,968 --> 00:33:46,717
Look here at this.
These radios are on sale real cheap.

349
00:33:46,764 --> 00:33:50,014
- You reckon we could get us one?
- (Doo groans)

350
00:33:56,815 --> 00:34:00,730
Here, you read that.
Then we'll talk radios.

351
00:34:03,280 --> 00:34:06,115
My gosh, Doo, this has got pictures in it.

352
00:34:11,747 --> 00:34:13,989
(Muttering)

353
00:34:17,878 --> 00:34:21,710
- (Whistles) Here, dog.
- (Dog barking)

354
00:34:33,352 --> 00:34:36,851
Oh, Loretty, that there book...

355
00:34:38,649 --> 00:34:42,860
That thing's helped
millions of people the world over.

356
00:34:42,903 --> 00:34:45,476
I thought it might do us a little good.

357
00:34:45,531 --> 00:34:48,781
I can't read this.
It's got big old words in it.

358
00:34:49,827 --> 00:34:52,318
Look at this one. Look.

359
00:34:52,371 --> 00:34:55,288
That dadgum word is a foot long.

360
00:34:55,332 --> 00:34:58,701
What's a foot-long word
supposed to mean?

361
00:35:01,255 --> 00:35:03,331
(Doo groaning)

362
00:35:06,593 --> 00:35:09,511
I don't need no book
to tell me what's wrong.

363
00:35:09,555 --> 00:35:14,430
You just need to be more patient
and gentle with me, honey, that's all.

364
00:35:15,686 --> 00:35:17,974
I just need a little more time.

365
00:35:19,148 --> 00:35:21,473
Give you a little more time.

366
00:35:21,525 --> 00:35:25,190
Let me add up all these things
I have to give you more time on.

367
00:35:25,237 --> 00:35:28,487
You need a little more time
to learn how to cook.

368
00:35:28,532 --> 00:35:32,861
You need a little more time
to learn how to clean the damn house.

369
00:35:32,911 --> 00:35:36,411
Plus you need more time
to learn how to love your man.

370
00:35:36,456 --> 00:35:39,790
Is there anything
you know how to do right now?

371
00:35:42,254 --> 00:35:45,837
- When you gonna get me that ring?
- (Doo groans)

372
00:35:45,883 --> 00:35:50,212
Stop making that noise.
You sound like an old bear growling.

373
00:35:51,638 --> 00:35:55,090
Where are you going?
Doo, are you leaving?

374
00:36:02,274 --> 00:36:05,441
No, I ain't leaving.

375
00:36:08,488 --> 00:36:11,940
(Peggy Sue)
Mommy, look who's here! Loretta!

376
00:36:13,952 --> 00:36:16,028
(Loretta) Hi. Hi, Peggy.

377
00:36:16,079 --> 00:36:18,950
- Hi.
- Look who's here, Dad!

378
00:36:18,999 --> 00:36:21,075
Look who's here, Dad!

379
00:36:22,169 --> 00:36:25,123
Hi, Mommy. Doo's throwed me out.

380
00:36:25,172 --> 00:36:29,964
Thank the Lord. Maybe it ain't too late
to save you from ruining your life.

381
00:36:30,010 --> 00:36:32,466
- Loretty, you home!
- Hi, Daddy.

382
00:36:33,847 --> 00:36:36,682
I believe married life's making you fat.

383
00:36:38,477 --> 00:36:40,434
Oh, no.

384
00:36:40,479 --> 00:36:43,480
(Girl) F, O, D...

385
00:36:43,523 --> 00:36:45,397
Ready, Loretta?

386
00:36:48,278 --> 00:36:51,896
The last time I seen you
was for a shot for the measles.

387
00:36:51,949 --> 00:36:54,819
Now you're married.
How do you like it?

388
00:36:54,868 --> 00:36:56,612
Fine.

389
00:36:59,122 --> 00:37:02,076
Except me and Doo is separated.

390
00:37:03,168 --> 00:37:07,118
Things happen pretty fast
between you and Doo, don't they?

391
00:37:25,732 --> 00:37:28,402
(Toots horn)

392
00:37:30,320 --> 00:37:31,980
Hey!

393
00:37:32,864 --> 00:37:35,865
(Doo) Hold up there.

394
00:37:35,909 --> 00:37:38,531
(Woman) Hey, Doolittle, how are you?

395
00:37:38,578 --> 00:37:41,532
- Good day, isn't it?
- It sure is.

396
00:37:41,581 --> 00:37:45,330
- (Woman) What have you been doing?
- Working too damn hard.

397
00:37:45,377 --> 00:37:48,212
- What about you?
- Hey, Doolittle Lynn.

398
00:37:49,298 --> 00:37:51,789
Who's that sow wallowing in your Jeep?

399
00:37:51,842 --> 00:37:55,709
- What did you call me?
- A sow. That's a woman pig.

400
00:38:04,021 --> 00:38:06,346
Hi, Loretta, I just...

401
00:38:06,398 --> 00:38:08,474
Hey, Loretta!

402
00:38:14,031 --> 00:38:18,527
- I was fixing to come see you.
- Was you gonna bring your girlfriend?

403
00:38:18,577 --> 00:38:21,946
She don't mean nothing.
I got something to tell you.

404
00:38:21,997 --> 00:38:24,203
I got something to tell you too.

405
00:38:25,959 --> 00:38:28,331
Loretta, I am leaving Kentucky.

406
00:38:29,671 --> 00:38:32,791
I'm going to Washington
to get me a job on a ranch.

407
00:38:32,841 --> 00:38:35,759
That damned coal mine's
got me buried alive.

408
00:38:35,802 --> 00:38:39,847
- Was you just gonna leave me?
- Just till I get the money to send for you.

409
00:38:39,890 --> 00:38:43,259
- What makes you think I'd come?
- You're my wife.

410
00:38:43,310 --> 00:38:47,142
I'm your wife! You better think
of a better reason than that.

411
00:38:47,189 --> 00:38:50,973
There ain't nothing for me
in Kentucky, Loretta.

412
00:38:51,026 --> 00:38:54,644
Except a chest full of coal dust
and being an old man time I'm 40.

413
00:38:56,114 --> 00:38:58,154
You ask your daddy.

414
00:38:58,950 --> 00:39:02,651
'Sides that, you got to come with me,
I love you.

415
00:39:02,704 --> 00:39:05,789
You promised Daddy
you wouldn't take me off far.

416
00:39:05,832 --> 00:39:10,790
You just have to decide
whether you're his daughter or my wife.

417
00:39:14,341 --> 00:39:17,425
Get in. I'll take you back to the house.

418
00:39:19,388 --> 00:39:21,629
What are you doing in the bottom?

419
00:39:21,681 --> 00:39:24,089
I come to see Doc Turner.

420
00:39:24,142 --> 00:39:26,051
You sick?

421
00:39:26,103 --> 00:39:28,475
Yeah, I'm gonna have a baby.

422
00:39:30,232 --> 00:39:33,601
(Chuckles) Oh, Lord, Loretta.

423
00:39:34,778 --> 00:39:39,321
Darlin', you might have found something
that you know how to do.

424
00:39:39,366 --> 00:39:42,035
Stop! Don't go so fast!

425
00:39:50,168 --> 00:39:52,244
(Chatting, indistinct)

426
00:40:04,391 --> 00:40:08,389
It's from Doo! He sent me the money
to come to Washington.

427
00:40:21,908 --> 00:40:26,617
She's late. Reckon she might have
jumped the tracks.

428
00:40:26,663 --> 00:40:29,747
Oh, Daddy, them things don't do that.

429
00:40:30,834 --> 00:40:34,666
- Do they?
- They've been known to.

430
00:40:36,590 --> 00:40:39,045
Get up here. Let's see what you weigh.

431
00:40:46,224 --> 00:40:49,142
117!

432
00:40:49,186 --> 00:40:52,186
Boy, this baby's gonna be a big one.

433
00:40:52,230 --> 00:40:55,433
- You weigh now.
- It wouldn't do no good.

434
00:40:55,484 --> 00:40:59,944
I wouldn't know how much was me
and how much was all that coal dust.

435
00:40:59,988 --> 00:41:02,064
(Train whistle)

436
00:41:09,122 --> 00:41:11,245
I ain't never gonna see you again.

437
00:41:12,334 --> 00:41:14,410
Yes, you will, Daddy.

438
00:41:15,504 --> 00:41:19,418
Maybe. But I ain't never gonna see
my little girl again.

439
00:41:22,052 --> 00:41:24,625
Them years has been robbed from me,

440
00:41:24,679 --> 00:41:27,052
like a thief broke in and robbed 'em.

441
00:41:43,823 --> 00:41:52,163
(Woman on radio) <i>♪ As I listen to
the words you are saying ♪</i>

442
00:41:52,207 --> 00:41:59,503
(With radio) ♪ It brings memories
when I was a trusting wife ♪

443
00:42:00,590 --> 00:42:08,254
♪ It wasn't God
who made honky tonk angels... ♪

444
00:42:08,306 --> 00:42:10,263
Thank you, Betty Sue.

445
00:42:10,308 --> 00:42:17,271
♪ As you said
in the words of your song ♪

446
00:42:17,315 --> 00:42:21,609
Ernest Ray, your Daddy is gonna
wear you out when he gets home.

447
00:42:21,653 --> 00:42:26,114
(With radio) ♪ ... married men
think they're still single ♪

448
00:42:32,289 --> 00:42:36,500
(Doo) Y'all scared of the rain?
Let's go to work, boys.

449
00:42:40,255 --> 00:42:43,007
(Doo) Come here, boy. Come here.

450
00:42:43,049 --> 00:42:44,793
Daddy, Daddy!

451
00:42:44,843 --> 00:42:46,919
How you doing?

452
00:42:48,179 --> 00:42:50,670
Hello, darlin'. Come here, baby.

453
00:42:52,934 --> 00:42:55,259
What did you do all day, baby?

454
00:42:55,312 --> 00:42:58,312
I put up 17 quarts of this apple butter.

455
00:42:58,356 --> 00:43:00,894
And Doo, the dadgum sink stopped up.

456
00:43:00,942 --> 00:43:03,564
I spent half the morning fixing that.

457
00:43:03,612 --> 00:43:07,858
- (Ernest ray whining)
- Jack Benny, stop kicking him.

458
00:43:07,907 --> 00:43:11,691
Do you hear me? And then I had
that doctor's appointment.

459
00:43:12,787 --> 00:43:16,737
It's a false alarm.
We'd better be a whole lot more careful.

460
00:43:16,791 --> 00:43:19,828
Cover your mouth
when you're coughing.

461
00:43:19,878 --> 00:43:22,665
And then I come home.

462
00:43:22,714 --> 00:43:24,457
Eat, boy.

463
00:43:24,507 --> 00:43:28,671
Betty Sue, you are not leaving this table
till you finish that.

464
00:43:28,720 --> 00:43:32,255
- Sit up. Come here.
- Then I come home and cooked supper.

465
00:43:32,307 --> 00:43:35,391
- And I'm about ready to die.
- (Kids chattering)

466
00:43:35,435 --> 00:43:38,471
- How was your day?
- Wet.

467
00:43:42,942 --> 00:43:45,398
- Hey, Mooney!
- Yo!

468
00:43:45,445 --> 00:43:49,110
Your momma called long distance
from Kentucky today,

469
00:43:49,157 --> 00:43:53,653
said happy anniversary
and why don't you call her more often.

470
00:43:53,703 --> 00:43:55,826
Much obliged.

471
00:43:55,872 --> 00:43:59,407
Why don't you have a phone put in
sometime, Mooney?

472
00:43:59,459 --> 00:44:01,748
We don't like telephones.

473
00:44:06,007 --> 00:44:09,875
(Loretta) ♪ The captain
he must have been drinkin' ♪

